observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
Inventory Committee/Property Custodian to reconcile their RPCI and RPCPPE with the records of the Municipal Accountant;
Municipal Accountant to (i) review the PPE account balances and draw journal entries to effect the necessary adjustments to correct the misclassified accounts and reclassify tangible items below the capitalization threshold of ₱15,0000 in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 and COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and (ii) henceforth, ensure that all purchased PPEs shall be recorded into appropriate accounts following the asset recognition principle and the capitalization threshold of ₱15,000.00.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
thru the Office of the Municipal Accountant, reconcile their records with GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth, review the over-remittance to Pag-IBIG amounting to ₱100.00 and make the necessary adjustments, if warranted;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to identify the employees whose GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth contributions or loan amortizations were still not remitted and effect the immediate remittance thereof;
thru the Agency Authorized Officer to report to the GSIS the updated list of all of its employees, their corresponding employment status, positions, salaries and such other pertinent information, including subsequent changes therein, if any, as required under Section 6.a of the IRR of R.A. No. 8291; and
henceforth, require the offices concerned to observe the remittance of mandatory contributions within the prescribed period to avoid payment of penalties.

With the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
the Municipal Engineer to submit all lacking documents such as the approved APP, Plans/Drawings and Specifications, and the Detailed Engineering Estimate of the LGU;
the BAC to i) submit all lacking bid documents to the Audit Team and henceforth adhere strictly to the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in all stages of procurement process and ensure that all bid documents are complete, evaluated, and submitted on time; and      ii) the BAC to justify/explain the reason for allowing the bidder to be declared as LCRB despite the submission of expired DTI Certificate and PCAB License and the Performance Bond with amount less than the required 30% of the contract amount;
the Municipal Accountant to submit the approved CAF; and
the BAC and contractor to use the prescribed bid form and contract agreement in the fifth (5th) edition of PBD issued by the GPPB.
